<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
In a parenthetical citation, when the author is anonymous, include the title of the web page in italics, immediately following the cited material. Abbreviate the title if it is longer than a noun phrase. For example, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Southern Novels</em> consists entirely of a noun phrase (a noun <em>Novels</em> preceded by two modifiers) and wouldnâ€™t be shortened. By contrast <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels of the South</em> would be shortened to its noun phrase <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels</em>. The abbreviated title should begin with the word by which it is alphabetised in the Works Cited. If the title does not begin with a noun phrase, cite the first word if it is enough to direct the reader to the correct entry. For further information on abbreviating titles, see 3.2.1 Abbreviating Titles of Sources in the <a href="http://west-sydney-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/UWS-ALMA:default_scope:UWS-ALMA21186157620001571" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MLA Handbook (8th edition)</a>.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (<em>Statistics New Zealand</em>).
</blockquote>
<br>
Or include the title in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	The data presented from <em>Statistics New Zealand</em> displays &#34;a trend towards an 
	ageing population&#34;.
</blockquote>
